{"id":"2107.10969","submitter":"David DeFazio","authors":"David DeFazio and Shiqi Zhang","title":"Leveraging Human Knowledge to Learn Quadruped Locomotion Policies","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.RO cs.AI","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Legged robots are versatile in navigating challenging terrains and\nenvironments that can be difficult to other robot platforms (e.g., the\nwheeled). Although there has been success in applying reinforcement learning\n(RL) methods to learn quadruped locomotion policies, there is little research\non how to effectively leverage rule-based human knowledge to facilitate this\nlearning process. In this paper, we develop an approach, referred to as RMLL,\ndemonstrating that human knowledge in the form of Linear Temporal Logic\nformulas can be applied to speed up the RL-based locomotion learning process,\nand to allow specifying different locomotion gaits. This is done without the\nuse of reference trajectories, another form of prior knowledge commonly used to\nspecify gait type and speed up RL-based locomotion learning. To achieve this,\nwe express our task as an automaton constructed under a recently developed\nframework called Reward Machine (RM). Experimental results in simulation show\nthat our RM-based approach better leverages this rule-based human knowledge\nwhen compared with competitive baselines, some of which also access this\nknowledge.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 23 Jul 2021 00:37:32 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 7 Mar 2022 15:39:29 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-03-08"}
